# Business Flowchart Rule

When the user asks for a business flowchart, first map the business parts, then create a flowchart only for the most important section.

## Writing Style

- Use simple, human words.
- Keep it short and clear.
- No buzzwords.
- No fluff.
- Use clear titles and short text under each title.
- Separate sections with:
`----------------------------`

## Required Output Order (Always Follow)

1) Break the business into clear parts.
2) Explain each part briefly.
3) Identify the most important part (core bottleneck or core value driver).
4) Build a flowchart for that part.
5) Add quick optimization notes for that flow.

## Section Template

 Business parts]
List all major parts in order (example: acquisition, onboarding, delivery, retention, payments, support).
----------------------------
 Part-by-part explanation]
Give 1-3 lines for each part: purpose, input, output.
----------------------------
 Most important section]
State which section is most critical and why.
----------------------------
 Flowchart]
Provide a clear text flowchart for the selected section.
Use one of these styles:
- Mermaid flowchart
- Arrow format (A -> B -> C)
----------------------------
 Improvement ideas]
Give 3-5 practical improvements for this flow.

## Flowchart Rules

- Keep flowchart focused on one section only.
- Include decision points where needed.
- Include failure points and fallback paths.
- Keep labels business-friendly and easy to read.
- If information is missing, ask short clarifying questions before final flowchart.

## Mermaid Default Format

Use this default style unless user asks otherwise:

```mermaid
flowchart TD
    A[Start] --> B[Step 1]
    B --> C{Decision}
    C -->|Yes| D[Path A]
    C -->|No| E[Path B]
    D --> F[End]
    E --> F
```

## Quality Rules

- Show the real user/business journey, not abstract theory.
- Prefer practical steps over technical jargon.
- Mention assumptions clearly if data is incomplete.
- Keep output actionable for decision-making.
